A superb surrealist piece."}, {"comment_author": "metamage", "comment_date": "04/02/2024", "comment_text": "This is quite an interesting piece. I've seen this in other works of yours in which you build up a psychological space with the techniques you've developed to support the subject matter. For me, you attempt to show the ineffable,  as if you identify types of energy eminating out of the whole of what you present. This element of atmospherics I speak of. .. you are playing with something larger than life and really fascinating. Do you have a vision of where you want to go with this? I see you as if you are punching through the common  mental spaces we share every day to expose the mystery that exists on a much larger, impersonal scale, woven underneath ... maybe it's particles or atoms flowing over the retina! You build these subtle landscapes and fill them with power."}, {"comment_author": "metamage", "comment_date": "03/02/2024", "comment_text": "Whaaaaa? I didn't write that last sentence, that garbled thought. No. Somebody else typed it for sure and snuck it in when I wasn't looking. That's the ticket! My unconscious has a lot of snark for a disembodied Ur-life form, but it likes me. And thus, speaking of such things, I had a wonderful day of revealing. I was directed to a tranch of hard-copies of my flash fiction stories, over 80 of them. And, so amazing to have found them, and my novels which I thought were all lost after so many absent years. A lot of chaos erupted when I was diagnosed with breast cancer, rampant diabetes and uncontrolled, highly neurotic blood-pressure. I remembered I'd then printed out EVERYTHING in a madly depressive fog, as parts of myself were lopped off and left in a pail for trash beside some dump off- road. The Colorado mountains were not my friend, then. They were ominous tricksters, and I wanted out. After the off-lopping  I was just haunting around. Many things got lost in time and space and moving out of storage facilities; and then 10 years later, I find them nested like bunnies, curled around each other. in fact, I found ALL OF MY WRITINGS, including three WIP novels, thank God. Surprise! Lost and found, lost and found. About  ten pounds of xerox prints. So! There you are. The unconscious provides as well as mysteriously hides, good things. I'm going to, oh, Lord, recreate them again in digital format to send in the clouds for safe keeping. (Reverse engineering for the Unconscious!) I was up to 150,000 words in one of the novels. That's a lot of words to lose as they were irreplaceable like lopped-off body parts sprinkled among ignored scenic way-stations. All stunningly resurrected from the netherworld of lost sub-plots. Gosh, now I'm responsible for them languishing unattended; lost and abandoned by none other their mother. Tragic. "}, {"comment_author": "metamage", "comment_date": "03/02/2024", "comment_text": "Great misty, hidden space, I love the need for the observer to peer into the surface. "}]
